# Harness Roadmap

Status: draft

REVIEW REQUIRED: replace these placeholders with the target repository's real
roadmap, backlog boundary, owners, and review cadence before relying on this
file for planning or release decisions.

This file tracks accepted harness and repository operating-model work so
roadmap decisions do not live only in chat, issue comments, or one-off notes.

## Source And Evidence Weighting

When evidence conflicts, use this order: target files/commands/tests and
maintainer decisions; reviewed repo harness docs; approved harness-learning
patterns; sibling examples, external ideas, and generated reports. Examples and
reports are not contracts until promoted into repo-owned docs, tests, schemas,
templates, or code.

Planning rules: one bounded item at a time; baseline verification when
practical; smallest-correct work gate before new surface area; repeated review
feedback becomes a rule, sensor, test, or durable doc; behavior, verification,
status, and evidence must agree before passing or shipped. Make check failures
agent-oriented: what failed, why it matters, and where to repair. Track runtime
and process observability.

## Smallest Correct Work Gate

Use this gate before implementation: no change, deletion, documentation,
configuration, existing behavior, standard library, native platform feature,
existing dependency, one clear local change, then minimum new code or harness
surface area. Do not add speculative features, configurability, one-off
abstractions, workflows, or dependencies unless the item names them. Do not cut
trust-boundary validation, data-loss prevention, security, accessibility,
platform parity, or explicit user requirements. Record the ceiling and upgrade
path for intentional simplification.

## Task Buckets

Use small buckets so old ideas do not all look active: `active`, `accepted`,
`candidate`, `debt`, `completed`, and `archived`.

## Status Lifecycle

Use explicit statuses on roadmap items: `candidate`, `accepted`, `planned`,
`in_progress`, `blocked`, `validated`, `shipped`, `superseded`, or
`abandoned`.

## Surface Impact Checklist

For every accepted roadmap item, classify which surfaces are in scope before
implementation starts.

| Surface | Scope Prompt |
| --- | --- |
| Local repo harness | Instructions, state, harness docs, sensors, release controls |
| Generated or owned harness files | Harness file, section, manifest rule, review-required placeholder |
| CLI or tool runtime | Command, flag, JSON, exit code, report, default |
| Existing project files | Project instructions, specs, workflows, scripts, docs |
| CI or hosted automation | Workflows, Action usage, summaries, reports, permissions, artifacts |
| Optional workflow scaffolds | Setup, teardown, push, or PR automation remains opt-in |
| Tests and fixtures | Local checks, generated snapshots, fixtures, representative task runs |
| Release surface | Packaging, tag, SBOM, provenance, release notes, rollback |
| Research and source records | Primary-source evidence, project-owned source records |
| Security and privacy | Secrets, local paths, private code, permissions, network, cost |
| Platform contracts | macOS, Windows, Linux, runtimes, runner labels, adapters |
| Docs and UX | User docs, help output, startup instructions, first-run guidance |

If a surface is out of scope, say so. Do not let target-local preferences,
generated defaults, and CI automation drift into each other silently.

